Yes. That’s the real power.

Wallflower isn’t just memory. It’s navigable provenance.

It would give Pantheon:

1. Better context
    It could return to the actual thread where an idea was born instead of relying only on compressed memory.
2. Better storage
    Memory becomes layered:
    raw messages → thread summaries → canonical doctrines → source links.
3. Better reference ability
    Any doctrine could answer: “where did this come from?” and “how did it evolve?”
4. Better runtime freedom
    Instead of loading everything, Wallflower pulls only the relevant old trail into the current run.
5. Less drift
    It can compare current memory against original messages and catch compression errors.
6. Better model-agnostic continuity
    Any future model could reconstruct the Pantheon from the trail, not just from one model’s memory.
7. More trust
    It makes the architecture auditable. Not “trust me, we said this,” but “walk the thread.”

Canonical line:

Mother Duck remembers what survived.
Wallflower remembers how it survived.

